The first step to playing notes on the Trombone is to understand slide positions.
This is the Trombone Slide, and the image we will use to show positions.

There are 7 positions on the Trombone. The first position is where the slide is all the way in, and your hand is closest to your face. We
call this First Position.

To play other positions, you extend your arm and move the slide
further away from your face.  The most important positions are
First, Third, and Fourth positions.  These are your “landmarks”
because they are easy to remember.

First Position is with the slide
closest to you.

Third Position is where the
start of the outer slide piece
meets the bell.

Fourth Position is where the
bar that you are holding
meets the bell.
Sixth Position is where you extend your arm just about as far as it will go.  This varies from person to person, so be sure to consult a teacher on proper technique.

This leaves Second and Fifth Positions.  The Second Position is about half way between the First and Third Positions, while the Fifth Position is about half way between the Fourth and Sixth Positions.  The Seventh Position is rarely used, but must be learned to play the full range of the Trombone.  Seventh Position is played by extending your arm out all the way.
Finally here are all the positions seen at once.
